                        <div xml:id="div_p28_en" hand="#h1" type="box_testo_en">
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa093" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa093" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>and we have seen new islands rise up one day from the surgace of some sea, but we have never known of a language which was not spoken the day before or which was not spoken in the same way the day before. 
                            </ab>
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa06994" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa094" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>One might refer here to Volapük. I was going to evoke it myself. For in truth Volapük and the other artificial languages are an excellent example which shows what prevents a langage from being born or what insures the transmission of those which exist: 
                            </ab>        
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa095" coresp="#pericope_91Aaaa095" xml:lang="EN">
                                <lb/>there are two factors, the first of which is the absence of initiative, each and every population being perfectly happy with the absence of initiative, each and every population being perfectly happy with its mother tongue; 
                            </ab>    
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa096" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa096" xml:lang="EN">                                
                                <lb/>and the second being that, even if an initiative came about, which in itself presupposes a whole cluster of quite exceptional circumstances, notably writing, this initiative would come up against the impenetrable resistance of the mass of speaker, who would not give up their customary idiom.
                            </ab>                            
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa097" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa097" xml:lang="EN">                                
                                <lb/>Volapük, which did not seek to unseat any existing language, has not, despite the favourable conditions in which it found itself, met witch great success in this world.
                            </ab>                            
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa098" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa098" xml:lang="EN">                                
                                <lb/>It may be said that to deny in this sense that any language is born is to play with words, and that one needs only to define what is meant by birth in order not to deny the birth or the progressive development of a language like German, or French. 
                            </ab>                            
                            <ab xml:id="en_91Aaaa099" corresp="#pericope_91Aaaa099" xml:lang="EN">                                
                                <lb/>I would answer that this is to play on another word which is the word language;
                            </ab>
                        </div>   
                    </body>
                </text>       
